## Summary

**Root cause:** In `packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts`, `merge()` set `checks: []` unconditionally, silently discarding all refinements from both operands — the same class of bug that was fixed for `.pick()`, `.omit()`, and `.partial()` in v4.3.0, but `merge()` was missed.

**Fix:** Added an upfront guard that throws when either operand carries checks (refinements), consistent with the sibling methods:

```ts
export function merge(a, b) {
  const aChecks = a._zod.def.checks;
  const bChecks = b._zod.def.checks;
  const hasChecks = (aChecks && aChecks.length > 0) || (bChecks && bChecks.length > 0);
  if (hasChecks) {
    throw new Error(".merge() cannot be used on object schemas containing refinements");
  }
  ...
}
```

Unlike `.pick()`/`.omit()` (single schema), `.merge()` takes two operands, so both `a` and `b` are checked. Now the PoC throws instead of silently returning a schema that lost its `.refine()` callback — surfacing the problem rather than producing a misleadingly-valid schema.

The fix is complete. None of the existing `.merge()` tests use refined schemas, so they won't be affected.

## Summary

**Root cause:** In `packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts`, the `merge()` function unconditionally set `checks: []`, silently discarding all `.refine()` refinements from both operands. This was inconsistent with `.pick()`, `.omit()`, and `.partial()`, which were updated in v4.3.0 to throw an explicit error rather than silently drop refinements.

**Fix:** Added a guard at the top of `merge()` that throws if *either* operand carries checks, matching the established pattern:

```ts
export function merge(a: schemas.$ZodObject, b: schemas.$ZodObject): any {
  const aChecks = a._zod.def.checks;
  const bChecks = b._zod.def.checks;
  if ((aChecks && aChecks.length > 0) || (bChecks && bChecks.length > 0)) {
    throw new Error(".merge() cannot be used on object schemas containing refinements");
  }
  ...
}
```

I checked both operands (not just `a`) because `merge` combines two schemas and a refinement on either side would be lost. The `checks: []` line in the def is now harmless — neither operand can have checks past the guard — so I left the rest of the function as-is to keep the diff minimal. The error message follows the exact `.pick()`/`.omit()`/`.partial()` wording for consistency.

All 3808 tests pass.

## Summary

**Root cause:** In `packages/zod/src/v4/core/regexes.ts`, the `cidrv6` regex used a hand-written IPv6 body — `([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4})?::([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4}:?){0,6}` — that only allows **0 or 1 hextet before `::`**. IPv6 addresses with 2+ groups before `::` (like the canonical `2001:db8::/32`) never matched. `$ZodCIDRv6` validates at runtime via `new URL()`, but still assigns this broken regex to `def.pattern`, which leaks into `z.toJSONSchema()` output — so the emitted `pattern` rejected valid CIDRs that Zod itself accepts.

**Fix:** Rebuilt `cidrv6` from the already-correct `ipv6` regex (which fully enumerates the eight compression alternatives), appending the `/prefix` suffix:

```ts
export const cidrv6: RegExp = /*@__PURE__*/ new RegExp(
  `^${ipv6.source.slice(1, -1)}\\/(12[0-8]|1[01][0-9]|[1-9]?[0-9])$`
);
```

This is option 1 from the report and follows the same DRY approach the file already uses (`cidrv4` mirrors `ipv4`). It keeps a useful `pattern` in the JSON schema while making it consistent with runtime behavior. All the reported inputs now match, invalid prefixes (`/129`) and non-IPs are still rejected, and the full test suite (3808 tests) passes.

## Summary

**Root cause:** `.default()` clones its default value on each parse via `util.shallowClone` (in `packages/zod/src/v4/core/api.ts`, the `defaultValue` getter). But `shallowClone` in `packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts` only handled plain objects (`{...o}`) and arrays (`[...o]`) — for any other object type, including `Map` and `Set`, it fell through to `return o`, handing back the **same reference** every time. So mutating a parsed default (e.g. `map.set(...)`) polluted the value returned by every subsequent `.parse(undefined)`.

**Fix:** Extended `shallowClone` to clone `Map` and `Set` instances:

```ts
export function shallowClone(o: any): any {
  if (isPlainObject(o)) return { ...o };
  if (Array.isArray(o)) return [...o];
  if (o instanceof Map) return new Map(o);
  if (o instanceof Set) return new Set(o);
  return o;
}
```

This fixes the reported symptom at its source (the clone utility used by `.default()`), so each parse now returns an independent `Map`/`Set`. Verified with a repro (both `Map` and `Set` defaults now return size-0 on each fresh parse) and confirmed the existing default/map/set test suites still pass (32 + 48 tests green).

Both repro tests pass with the fix (the earlier "failed" was just the wrong import path). Temp file removed.

## Root cause

`.default()` value getters (in `classic/schemas.ts`, `mini/schemas.ts`, and `core/api.ts`) return `util.shallowClone(defaultValue)` for non-function defaults, so each parse should get a fresh copy. But `shallowClone` only handled plain objects (`{...o}`) and arrays (`[...o]`):

```ts
export function shallowClone(o: any): any {
  if (isPlainObject(o)) return { ...o };
  if (Array.isArray(o)) return [...o];
  return o;   // Map, Set, etc. fell through → same reference every time
}
```

A `Map`/`Set` is neither a plain object nor an array, so it hit the `return o` fallback — the *same reference* was handed back on every `.parse(undefined)`. Mutating the parsed result therefore mutated the schema's stored default, so a second parse of the same input produced a different (already-mutated) value.

## Fix

Extended `shallowClone` in `packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts` to shallow-copy `Map` and `Set`:

```ts
export function shallowClone(o: any): any {
  if (isPlainObject(o)) return { ...o };
  if (Array.isArray(o)) return [...o];
  if (o instanceof Map) return new Map(o);
  if (o instanceof Set) return new Set(o);
  return o;
}
```

This is the shared helper used by all the default-value getters, so the fix covers classic, mini, and the core API in one place, and matches the existing shallow-copy semantics for objects/arrays. The existing `shallowClone` test still passes.

## Summary

**Root cause:** `floatSafeRemainder` in `packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts` counted decimal places for `val` with a naive `val.toString().split(".")[1].length`. For small numbers, JS `toString()` yields scientific notation — `(2.5e-7).toString()` is `"2.5e-7"`, so this counted the fractional part `"5e-7"` as 4 decimal places instead of the true 8. With too few decimal places, `val.toFixed(decCount)` rounded the value down to a clean multiple of the step, so `valInt % stepInt` came out `0` and non-multiples were silently accepted.

The code already special-cased scientific notation for the *step*, but that branch only fired when `stepDecCount === 0`, so it also broke for steps with a fractional mantissa like `2.5e-7`.

**Fix:** Extracted a `decimalPlaces` helper that parses both a fractional mantissa and a negative exponent, returning `fracCount + exp`. Both `val` and `step` now use it, so scientific notation is handled uniformly:

```ts
function decimalPlaces(num: number): number {
  const str = num.toString();
  const [base, expPart] = str.split(/e-/i);
  const exp = expPart ? Number.parseInt(expPart) : 0;
  const fracCount = (base.split(".")[1] || "").length;
  return fracCount + exp;
}
```

**Verification:**
- `2.5e-7 % 1e-7` → `5e-8` (now correctly rejected), `3.3e-7` → `3e-8` (rejected), `3e-7` → `0` (still accepted).
- Classic float cases (`0.3 % 0.1`, `0.1 % 0.01`) still return `0`.
- Existing number/bigint/computed test suites pass (72 tests, no type errors). No test files were modified.
